        args='{"prompt":"What are the useful lives of property, plant and equipment, particularly for AI infrastructure (data centers, GPUs, supercomputers), satellites, launch vehicles, and ground stations in {{spacex_s1}}? Please provide the depreciation policies and useful life ranges disclosed."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What are the useful lives of property, plant and equipment, particularly for AI infrastructure (data centers, GPUs, supercomputers), satellites, launch vehicles, and ground stations in {{spacex_s1}}? Please provide the depreciation policies and useful life ranges disclosed.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures, here are the depreciation policies and estimated useful lives for the company\'s property, plant, and equipment (PP&E), with a specific focus on AI infrastructure, satellites, launch vehicles, and ground stations.\n\n### **General Depreciation Policies**\n*   **Method:** PP&E is stated at cost less accumulated depreciation. Assets are depreciated primarily using the **straight-line method** over their estimated useful lives.\n*   **Exception for Reusable Vehicles:** Flight vehicles and spacecraft are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** rather than a time-based useful life. \n*   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n*   **Refurbishment & Maintenance:** Routine maintenance and repairs are expensed as incurred. Significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase an asset\'s functionality, output, or expected life are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the asset\'s identified useful life.\n*   **Capitalized Interest:** Interest is capitalized during the construction period for significant long-term projects, such as AI infrastructure data centers and launch facilities. \n*   **Useful Life Revisions:** Management periodically reviews useful life estimates with engineering and operations teams. If the useful lives or expected remaining flights are found to be shorter or longer than originally estimated, the depreciation rate is adjusted prospectively.\n\n---\n\n### **Estimated Useful Lives by Asset Category**\nThe company discloses the following estimated useful life ranges for its PP&E categories:\n\n| Asset Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Servers and networking equipment** (GPUs, AI compute) | 5 - 6 years |\n| **Satellites** | 3 - 5 years |\n| Machinery and equipment | 3 - 10 years |\n| **Flight vehicle hardware** (Launch vehicles) | 5 - 25 flights |\n| **Data center infrastructure** | 20 - 25 years |\n| **Launch sites** | 7 - 20 years |\n| Buildings and improvements | 30 years |\n| Leasehold improvements | Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease |\n\n---\n\n### **Specifics on Requested Asset Categories**\n\n#### **1. AI Infrastructure (Data Centers, GPUs, Supercomputers)**\nAI infrastructure is split into two primary PP&E categories based on its physical components:\n*   **Servers and networking equipment (GPUs/Supercomputers):** 5 to 6 years. (The text notes the company is acquiring third-party GPUs, manufacturing its own GPUs, and constructing/leasing data centers to support AI products).\n*   **Data center infrastructure (The physical facilities):** 20 to 25 years. \n*   *Note on Construction:* The company has a massive "Construction-in-progress" balance primarily related to ongoing facility expansions and AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service. Interest is actively being capitalized on these AI data center construction projects.\n\n#### **2. Satellites**\n*   **Useful Life:** 3 to 5 years.\n*   **Specifics:** The company estimates broadband satellites have a **5-year useful life**, while first-generation mobile satellites have a **3-year useful life**. \n*   **Estimation Factors:** Useful lives are based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer technology. \n*   **Capitalized Costs:** Satellite costs include parts, labor, allocated overhead, and capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to put them into orbit. The company notes that the useful life of satellites is inherently shorter than the IT systems they host, requiring periodic replacement launches.\n\n#### **3. Launch Vehicles (Flight Vehicle Hardware)**\n*   **Useful Life:** 5 to 25 flights (depreciated based on expected average flights, not years).\n*   **Estimation Factors:** The expected number of flights is determined by: (1) the continued ability to successfully recover and refurbish hardware, (2) the economic feasibility of incremental flights (supported by declining refurbishment costs), and (3) customer acceptance for reflown hardware. \n*   **Asset Composition:** Boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, and Dragon capsules are reusable and classified as PP&E. Second stages are not reusable and are classified as inventory. Starship is currently in development, with a majority of its costs expensed to Research & Development as incurred.\n\n#### **4. Ground Stations**\n*   **Useful Life:** Not explicitly broken out as a standalone line item in the useful life table. However, the text mentions "gateway decommissions" alongside routine asset disposals and scrapping. Ground stations/gateways are most likely classified under **Machinery and equipment (3 to 10 years)** or potentially **Launch sites (7 to 20 years)** depending on their specific function and permanence.',
