ructure | 20–25 years |\n| Launch sites | 7–20 years |\n| Buildings and improvements | 30 years |\n| Leasehold improvements | Shorter of 7–20 years or lease life |\n\n---\n\n## Capital Expenditures by Segment\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Space | $1,052 | $759 | $3,832 | $2,032 | $1,497 |\n| Connectivity | 1,332 | 814 | 4,178 | 3,498 | 2,455 |\n| AI | 7,723 | 2,567 | 12,727 | 5,633 | 463 |\n| **Total CapEx** | **$10,107** | **$4,140** | **$20,737** | **$11,163** | **$4,415** |\n\nThe AI segment\'s capital expenditures surged from $463 million in 2023 to $12.7 billion in 2025, and reached $7.7 billion in just the first quarter of 2026 alone—exceeding all of FY 2024.\n\n---\n\n## Forward-Looking Statements on Future Capital Expenditures and AI Infrastructure\n\nThe document contains several explicit forward-looking statements regarding future investment plans:\n\n### 1. Substantial Increase in Capital Expenditures Expected\n> "We have incurred significant capital expenditures and **expect to increase our capital expenditures substantially in the future** in connection with the design, development, and deployment of our satellite constellations, launch vehicles, ground stations, manufacturing facilities, and programs, including **Terafab, AI compute infrastructure, data centers, and other supporting infrastructure**."\n\n### 2. AI-Specific Investment Plans\n> "We have made and **intend to continue to make substantial capital expenditures to support the growth of our AI products**, including costs related to **obtaining third-party GPUs, manufacturing our own GPUs, and constructing, leasing, maintaining, enhancing, and expanding our data centers**."\n\n### 3. Acceleration Option\n> "We **may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of any of these investments at any time**, which could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."\n\n### 4. Starship-Driven Cost Reduction Enabling Orbital AI\n> "We believe that Starship can eventually **reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more** relative to the historical average launch cost per kilogram according to NASA of $18,500, establishing a **scalable path to creating the infrastructure of the future, such as orbital AI compute**."\n\n### 5. Orbital AI Compute Satellite Deployment\n> The company references "potential deployment of our **orbital AI compute satellites as early as 2028**," including the ability to "successfully develop, scale, and commercialize such technologies, which are subject to significant technical complexity, capital requirements, new innovations and regulatory approvals."\n\n### 6. IPO Proceeds Allocation\n> "We intend to use the net proceeds from this offering to fund our growth strategy, including the **expansion of our AI compute infrastructure, enhancements to our launch infrastructure and launch vehicles, increases in the scale and capacity of our satellite constellations**, and any remaining amounts for general corporate purposes."\n\n### 7. Starship Capital Requirements\n> "The development, testing, and deployment of Starship in accordance with our anticipated schedule, as well as our pursuit of orbital AI, other space-related services, and lunar and interplanetary missions, **will require the investment of significant additional capital resources**."\n\n---\n\n## Additional Context\n\n- **Capitalized interest**: $169 million was capitalized into CIP for the year ended December 31, 2025 (related to AI infrastructure data centers), and $7 million for the three months ended March 31, 2026. No interest was capitalized in 2024 or 2023.\n- **Depreciation expense**: $5,915 million (FY 2025), $2,977 million (FY 2024), and $2,329 million (Q1 2026).\n- **Impairment charges**: $38 million in FY 2025 (damaged flight vehicle in Space segment; abandoned production line and damaged satellite hardware in Connectivity segment) and $24 million in Q1 2025 (damaged flight vehicles in Space segment). Additional restructuring-related impairments of $36 million (2024) and $54 million (2023) related to leasehold improvements and office equipment in the AI segment.\n- **Related-party PP&E additions**: $506 million (2025) and $191 million (2024) of Megapack products purchased from Tesla, plus $131 million of Cybertrucks, all recorded in PP&E.',
