        output='Based on the provided S-1 preamble excerpts, the company discloses a comprehensive, highly vertically integrated strategy for its AI infrastructure, centering on the COLOSSUS supercomputer, massive capital expenditures, and future expansion into orbital AI. \n\nHere is a detailed breakdown of the disclosures regarding the Colossus supercomputer, data center expansion, GPU purchases, and future investment commitments:\n\n### 1. The COLOSSUS Supercomputer and Current GPU Deployment\nThe company highlights its existing gigawatt-scale AI training clusters as a primary competitive advantage, emphasizing rapid deployment and cost efficiency:\n*   **Current Capacity:** COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II collectively provide approximately **1.0 gigawatt of compute power**, with additional power capacity available for operations. COLOSSUS II is located in Memphis, Tennessee.\n*   **Rapid Deployment:** The first cluster of COLOSSUS was brought online in **122 days** by repurposing an existing factory. The first cluster of COLOSSUS II was deployed even faster, in **91 days**. (The company notes the industry benchmark for bringing a 100MW greenfield data center online is approximately two years).\n*   **GPU Deployment Milestones:** \n    *   **COLOSSUS:** First cluster deployed approximately 100,000 H100 processors (~130 megawatts).\n    *   **COLOSSUS II:** First cluster deployed approximately 110,000 GB200 processors (~210 megawatts) in 91 days. The second cluster added 110,000 GB300 processors and 220 megawatts in just 64 days. The company states COLOSSUS II was one of the world\'s first data centers to deploy GB200s and GB300s at significant scale.\n\n### 2. AI Data Center Expansion and Buildout Plans\nThe company outlines aggressive terrestrial expansion plans for COLOSSUS II, alongside a visionary long-term plan for orbital data centers:\n*   **COLOSSUS II Expansion:** The next phase of expansion at COLOSSUS II is designed to train the next-generation Grok 5 AI model. Once fully operational, this phase will bring online **at least 220,000 additional GB300 processors** and represent an **additional 400+ megawatts of compute capacity**.\n*   **Power and Cooling Infrastructure:** COLOSSUS II is capable of operating entirely off a self-built, behind-the-meter gigawatt-scale natural gas power plant, supplemented by the world’s largest Megapack (battery storage) deployment. The facilities use brownfield retrofits, advanced direct-to-chip liquid cooling, high-density rack layouts, and advanced water reclamation. The company pledges to cover the costs of all new power delivery infrastructure upgrades so expenses are not passed on to local households.\n*   **Orbital AI Compute (Forward-Looking):** The company plans to eventually move power-intensive AI workloads into orbit to leverage near-constant solar energy, bypassing terrestrial energy constraints. They believe their Starship launch vehicle will enable the deployment and operation of orbital data centers that could eventually achieve lower costs than terrestrial data centers.\n\n### 3. GPU Purchases and Chip Manufacturing (Terafab)\nTo secure the massive compute required and alleviate future chip shortages, the company is vertically integrating into hardware manufacturing:\n*   **Third-Party GPUs:** The company incurs substantial costs related to obtaining third-party GPUs.\n*   **Terafab Initiative:** Together with Tesla (and Intel, which joined in April 2026), the company is building a manufacturing facility capable of producing **1 terawatt per year of compute hardware**. This "shovels-to-tokens" approach extends their vertical integration into chip design and manufacturing to optimize performance and reduce overall compute costs.\n\n### 4. AI Infrastructure Investment Commitments & Capex (Forward-Looking)\nThe S-1 details massive financial commitments and warns that prioritizing these long-term investments may impact near-term profitability:\n*   **Historical Capex Surge:** AI capital expenditures increased from $463 million in 2023 to $5.6 billion in 2024, and surged to **$12.7 billion in 2025**. These investments were primarily driven by the rapid expansion of terrestrial data centers.\n*   **Future Capex Expectations:** The company expects to *increase capital expenditures substantially* in the future for the design, development, and deployment of satellite constellations, launch vehicles, Terafab, AI compute infrastructure, and data centers. This includes manufacturing their own GPUs and constructing, leasing, maintaining, and expanding data centers.\n*   **Recent Financial Commitments:**\n    *   An **$8.5 billion deferred services fee** under a compute agreement (payable in cash or Class A common stock).\n    *   A **five-year equipment lease agreement with Valor** for AI infrastructure hardware ("Valor transaction III") for total undiscounted lease payments of **$6.58 billion**.\n    *   An asset purchase agreement to buy mobile gas turbines and related packages for approximately **$2 billion** to help provide power to the data centers.\n    *   A cloud services agreement with Anthropic PBC for access to compute capacity, with monthly fees ramping through May 2029.\n*   **Near-Term Profitability Warning:** The company explicitly states it may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of these investments at any time, which "could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."',
