    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Capital Expenditures and Future Depreciation: Key Disclosures\n\n## The Direct Relationship: Rising CapEx Driving Accelerating Depreciation\n\nThe company\'s disclosures reveal a clear and dramatic trajectory where capital expenditures—particularly in AI—are fueling a rapidly growing depreciation base:\n\n### Capital Expenditure Growth (Total and AI Segment)\n\n| Period | Total CapEx | AI Segment CapEx | AI as % of Total |\n|--------|------------|-----------------|-----------------|\n| 2023 | $4,415M | $463M | ~10% |\n| 2024 | $11,163M | $5,633M | ~50% |\n| 2025 | $20,737M | $12,727M | ~61% |\n| Q1 2026 | $10,107M | $7,723M | ~76% |\n\n### Corresponding Depreciation Expense Growth\n\n| Period | Total D&A | AI Segment D&A |\n|--------|----------|---------------|\n| 2023 | $2,635M | $1,180M |\n| 2024 | $3,824M | $1,679M |\n| 2025 | $5,915M | (not separately disclosed in these chunks) |\n| Q1 2025 | $1,237M | — |\n| Q1 2026 | $2,329M (per PP&E note) / $2,442M (per segment table) | $1,493M |\n\nThe depreciation expense nearly **doubled** from 2024 to 2025 ($2,977M to $5,915M), and Q1 2026 depreciation ($2,329M) already approximates **88% of full-year 2024 depreciation**—a direct consequence of the massive AI capital expenditures being placed in service.\n\n### The Growing Asset Base\n\nThe Property, Plant, and Equipment note (Note 5) reveals the scale of assets being deployed:\n\n- **Total PP&E (gross)** grew from $55,303M (Dec 2025) to $68,571M (Mar 2026)—a $13.3B increase in a single quarter\n- **Servers and networking equipment** alone total $23,850M, representing the largest asset category\n- **Construction-in-progress** surged from $4,604M (Dec 2025) to $14,045M (Mar 2026), indicating that approximately $14B of additional AI infrastructure is under construction and **not yet being depreciated**—representing a substantial future depreciation pipeline\n- Accumulated depreciation stands at only $14,692M against $68,571M gross PP&E, meaning the vast majority of the asset base is relatively new and early in its depreciation cycle\n\n---\n\n## Risk Factors and Disclosures About AI Infrastructure Impact\n\n### 1. Multi-Year Investment Horizon Before Profitability\n\nThe Risk Factors section explicitly warns:\n\n> *"We plan to allocate substantial capital to build our AI compute infrastructure, and we expect a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA. Our AI segment has incurred significant operating losses since inception, and we may not achieve profitability in this segment, or, if achieved, sustain it, and there can be no assurance that the returns on our AI investments will be adequate to justify the capital deployed."*\n\n### 2. Deliberate Prioritization of Long-Term Growth Over Near-Term Profitability\n\n> *"We may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of any of these investments at any time, which could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."*\n\n### 3. Increasing Operating Expenses Expected\n\n> *"We also expect our capital expenditures and operating expenses to increase in the future, including our general and administrative expenses as a result of increased costs associated with operating as a public company and as we continue to invest for our future growth, including substantial capital expenditures to design, develop, expand, and maintain our technologies and infrastructure to support our operations."*\n\n### 4. Scaling Law Uncertainty\n\nThe company introduces a unique risk that the fundamental economic premise of its AI investment could falter:\n\n> *"The continued improvement of AI model capabilities has historically depended in part on scaling laws, the empirical observation that model performance improves with increased compute, data, and model size, but there is uncertainty as to how long these scaling relationships will continue to hold."*\n\nThis is significant because if scaling laws diminish, the massive capital expenditures (and resulting depreciation) may not generate commensurate revenue or returns.\n\n### 5. Capitalized Interest Adding to the Asset Base\n\nThe company capitalizes interest during construction of AI data centers—$169M in 2025 and $7M in Q1 2026—which is included in Construction-in-Progress and will eventually be depreciated once assets are placed in service, further increasing future depreciation expense.\n\n### 6. Satellite Useful Life Sensitivity\n\nThe critical accounting estimates disclosure quantifies the material sensitivity of operating income to depreciation assumptions:\n\n> *"If the average useful life of our satellite assets had been changed by one year, it would have an approximately $480 million and $170 million impact on our operating income for the year ended December 31, 2025 and three months ended March 31, 2026, respectively."*\n\n### 7. Shorter Satellite Lifespans Truncating IT Infrastructure Life\n\nA distinctive risk for the company\'s space-based AI infrastructure:\n\n> *"The useful life of our satellites is inherently shorter than that of the information technology systems and infrastructure they host. As a result, we must periodically launch replacement satellites as existing satellites reach the end of their useful lives and are decommissioned, which may truncate the effective lifespan of those underlying information technology systems and infrastructure."*\n\nThis means depreciation expense could accelerate if satellite end-of-life forces earlier retirement of hosted computing assets.\n\n### 8. Space Weather and Asset Damage Risks\n\n> *"Space weather events, such as geomagnetic storms, solar flares, and other forms of radiation activity, have in the past disrupted and could in the future disrupt satellite propulsion, power systems, and communications equipment, potentially leading to reduced performance or permanent damage... Failures or performance degradation resulting from these risks could delay deployments, reduce available capacity, increase operating costs, require significant capital expenditures to replace affected assets."*\n\nThe company has already recorded impairment charges for damaged assets—$38M in 2025 and $24M in Q1 2025—primarily for damaged flight vehicles in the Space segment.\n\n### 9. Orbital AI Market Uncertainty\n\n> *"We may be required to devote financial, technical, human or other resources in excess of our current expectations, and there can be no assurance that these investments will generate adequate revenue."*\n\n### 10. AI Segment Losses Quantified\n\nThe actual financial impact of these investments is stark:\n\n| Period | AI Revenue | AI Loss from Operations | AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA |\n|--------|-----------|------------------------|---------------------------|\n| 2023 | $2,961M | $(3,973)M | — |\n| 2024 | $2,620M | $(1,561)M | — |\n| 2025 | $3,201M | $(6,355)M | $(1,237)M |\n| Q1 2026 | $818M | $(2,469)M | $(609)M |\n\n---\n\n## Summary Assessment\n\nThe company\'s disclosures paint a picture of **extraordinary capital intensity** with a clear and direct linkage to future depreciation and operating expenses:\n\n1. **The depreciation pipeline is enormous**: $14B in construction-in-progress (primarily AI infrastructure) has not yet begun depreciating, and the company is adding to it at a rate of approximately $7-8B per quarter in the AI segment alone.\n\n2. **Depreciation is already accelerating dramatically**: Total depreciation nearly doubled year-over-year from 2024 to 2025, and Q1 2026 annualized run-rate (~$9.3B) would represent another ~57% increase over 2025.\n\n3. **The company explicitly acknowledges the profitability risk**: Multiple risk factors warn that returns may not justify the capital deployed, that a multi-year horizon exists before positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA, and that scaling laws underpinning the investment thesis may not hold.\n\n4. **Useful life estimates are material and uncertain**: A one-year change in satellite useful life assumptions moves operating income by $480M annually, and the interaction between satellite lifespans and hosted IT infrastructure creates additional depreciation acceleration risk.\n\n5. **The company is deliberately accepting near-term losses**: Management explicitly states it may prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance, resulting in "periods of reduced profitability or increased losses."',
