.64%**\n- FY2024: $5,633M / $2,620M = **215.00%**\n- FY2025: $12,727M / $3,201M = **397.59%**\n- Q1 2026 alone: $7,723M (annualized ~$30.9B)\n\n**AI Segment D&A Trend:**\n- FY2023: $1,180M\n- FY2024: $1,679M\n- FY2025: $3,568M\n- Q1 2026: $1,493M (annualized ~$5,972M — already ~67% above FY2025)\n\nThe AI segment\'s D&A is already on a steep upward trajectory, but it is lagging the capex ramp, confirming the depreciation expansion thesis.\n\n### 4. The CIP Pipeline — A Leading Indicator of Future Depreciation\n\n| Period | Construction-in-Progress |\n|---|---|\n| Dec 31, 2024 | $3,007M |\n| Dec 31, 2025 | $4,604M |\n| Mar 31, 2026 | **$14,045M** |\n\nCIP is described as "primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service." The CIP balance **tripled in a single quarter** (Q1 2026), and none of it is currently being depreciated. Once placed in service, this $14B+ pipeline will flow directly into the depreciation base.\n\n### 5. Useful-Life Mix Favors Faster Depreciation in AI\n\nThe disclosed useful lives are:\n\n| Asset Category | Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| Servers and networking equipment (GPUs/AI compute) | 5–6 years |\n| Data center infrastructure | 20–25 years |\n| Satellites | 3–5 years |\n| Flight vehicle hardware | 5–25 flights |\n| Machinery and equipment | 3–10 years |\n\nAt YE2025, the AI-relevant PP&E categories were:\n- Servers and networking equipment: **$22,694M**\n- Data center infrastructure: $2,960M\n\nServers/networking equipment represents **~88.5%** of these two AI-relevant categories and carries the **shortest useful life (5–6 years)**. This means the bulk of AI capex will depreciate rapidly once placed in service.\n\n### 6. Quantifying the Implied Depreciation Expansion\n\nApplying the disclosed useful lives and the observed ~88%/12% mix between servers/networking and data center infrastructure:\n\n- **FY2025 AI capex ($12,727M)** → implied annual depreciation ≈ ($12,727M × 0.88 / 5.5) + ($12,727M × 0.12 / 22.5) ≈ **$2,104M/year**\n- **Q1 2026 CIP ($14,045M)** → implied annual depreciation ≈ ($14,045M × 0.88 / 5.5) + ($14,045M × 0.12 / 22.5) ≈ **$2,322M/year**\n\nCombined, these two pools alone imply roughly **$4.4B of incremental annual depreciation** once fully placed in service — versus the AI segment\'s current FY2025 D&A of $3,568M. This suggests the AI segment\'s depreciation could more than double over the next several years, even before considering additional capex.\n\n### 7. Corroborating Disclosures\n\nThe S-1 explicitly supports the depreciation-expansion thesis for AI:\n- "We have incurred significant capital expenditures and **expect to increase our capital expenditures substantially in the future** in connection with... Terafab, AI compute infrastructure, data centers, and other supporting infrastructure."\n- "We... **intend to continue to make substantial capital expenditures to support the growth of our AI products**, including costs related to obtaining third-party GPUs, manufacturing our own GPUs, and constructing, leasing, maintaining, enhancing, and expanding our data centers."\n- "We plan to allocate substantial capital to build our AI compute infrastructure, and we expect a **multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA**."\n- Capitalized interest of $169M (FY2025) and $7M (Q1 2026) on AI data center construction further enlarges the future depreciable base.\n\n---\n\n### Assumptions Required to Support the Conclusion\n\nThe conclusion that the AI segment will experience the most future depreciation expansion depends on the following assumptions, several of which are explicitly forward-looking and uncertain:\n\n1. **Capex continues at or above FY2025 levels.** The S-1 explicitly states this expectation, but it is a forward-looking statement. If scaling laws diminish (a risk the company itself flags) or if AI revenue fails to materialize, capex could be curtailed.\n\n2. **CIP converts to in-service PP&E on the expected timeline.** The $14B+ CIP balance must be completed and placed in service to begin depreciating. Construction delays, power-constraint issues, or supply-chain bottlenecks (e.g., GPU availability) could defer placement in service.\n\n3. **Useful lives remain at disclosed ranges (5–6 years for servers/networking; 20–25 years for data centers).** The company notes it "periodically reviews useful life estimates" and adjusts prospectively. If GPU useful lives are extended (e.g., due to software optimization or longer hardware viability), depreciation would be lower; if shortened (e.g., due to rapid obsolescence), depreciation would accelerate. The S-1 separately warns that satellite end-of-life may "truncate the effective lifespan of those underlying information technology systems and infrastructure," which could accelerate depreciation for any orbital AI assets.\n\n4. **No material impairments or early retirements.** Impairments would accelerate expense recognition (hitting the income statement immediately rather than over the useful life) but would reduce the future depreciation run-rate. The company has already recorded impairments ($38M in FY2025; $24M in Q1 2025), so this is a real risk.\n\n5. **Straight-line depreciation continues for AI infrastructure.** The company uses straight-line for PP&E generally (flight vehicles are the exception, depreciated by expected flights). A change in method would alter the timing.\n\n6. **The asset mix remains weighted toward shorter-lived servers/networking equipment.** If future AI capex shifts toward longer-lived data center infrastructure (20–25 years) or away from GPUs, the depreciation ramp would be slower.\n\n7. **Capitalized interest continues to add to the depreciable base.** The company is capitalizing interest on AI data center construction; this practice increases the gross depreciable base.\n\n8. **Revenue growth does not outpace capex growth sufficiently to normalize capex intensity.** Even if AI revenue scales, absolute depreciation will expand as long as the gross asset base grows. However, if revenue scales dramatically faster than capex, the *relative* depreciation burden would decline.\n\n9. **Lease vs. own mix does not shift materially off-balance-sheet.** The company has entered into a $6.58B five-year equipment lease with Valor ("Valor transaction III") for AI infrastructure hardware. A shift toward leasing (vs. owning) would move some depreciation off the company\'s books and into lease expense, altering the depreciation-expansion profile.\n\n10. **No major dispositions or asset sales.** Sale-leaseback or asset-sale transactions would remove assets from the depreciation base.\n\n---\n\n### Why the Other Segments Are Less Likely to Lead Depreciation Expansion\n\n- **Connectivity (Starlink):** Capex intensity is moderate (36.69%), and the D&A/Capex ratio (56.87%) is the highest of the three segments, indicating depreciation is already more closely tracking capex. Satellites have short lives (3–5 years), so depreciation will continue to grow, but the absolute scale of incremental capex (~$4.2B in FY2025) is far below AI\'s $12.7B. The S-1 quantifies satellite useful-life sensitivity: a one-year change in satellite useful life moves operating income by ~$480M (FY2025), which is material but smaller than the AI depreciation pipeline.\n\n- **Space (Launch):** Capex intensity is high (93.78%), but absolute capex ($3.8B) is the smallest of the three segments. Flight vehicles are depreciated by expected flights (5–25 flights) rather than time, and Starship costs are largely expensed to R&D as incurred (not capitalized), limiting the depreciation base. The Space segment\'s D&A grew only ~33% over two years (FY2023–FY2025), versus AI\'s ~3× growth.\n\n---\n\n### Bottom Line\n\nThe **AI segment** is the clear candidate for future depreciation expansion. It combines (i) the highest capex intensity by a wide margin (~398% in FY2025), (ii) a low current D&A/Capex ratio (~28%) indicating depreciation has not yet caught up to investment, (iii) a $14B+ CIP pipeline not yet being depreciated, (iv) a dominant asset category (servers/networking equipment) with the shortest useful life (5–6 years), and (v) explicit forward-looking statements that capex will increase substantially. The conclusion is supported by the filing\'s own disclosures, but it depends critically on the assumptions above — particularly continued capex at scale, timely placement of CIP into service, and stable useful-life estimates.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Reporting, MD&A, Property Plant and Equipment Note, Significant Accounting Policies, and Risk Factors"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
